dataObject.dc:title: Nesting habitat
dataObject.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Reproduction
dataObject.dc:description: So far as is known, Spotted Barbtails breed exclusively in riparian zones, directly over flowing mountain streams.

dataObject.dc:title: Nest description
dataObject.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Reproduction
dataObject.dc:description:
--From Greeney 2011 (http://neotropical.birds.cornell.edu/portal/species/lifehistory?p_p_spp=43736)--

Spotted Barbtails show remarkable variability in nest architecture, mostly in relation to the amount of material that adults bring and the degree to which surrounding material forms part of the nest. Nevertheless, most nests are of the same basic architectural design: large, globular, mossy balls with a downward facing entrance tube. The downward opening entrance into the nest chamber is slightly wider than tall, with the entrance flaring laterally, but with the height of the entrance maintained along the length of the tube. The inner chamber has an elevated front lip that serves to contain the nest contents as well as to form the inner portion of the entrance tube. Although this description applies to the majority of nests, many nests are variously constructed such that one or several portions of the outer nest structure are actually formed by part of the surrounding substrate. Thus, large portions of the inner chamber are often devoid of moss, and instead formed by the clay or wood to which the nest is attached.

dataObject.dc:title: Nest of Slate-throated Whitestart
dataObject.dc:description:
Nest of Slate-throated Whitestart

Finca Chaupi Chupa, east of Nayon, Quito, prov Pichincha 2250 m

The nest was found 8-jan-2009 destroyed. The adults were seen building the nest in december 2008 almost on the ground in some dead cut grass. That grass was removed by the farmer and the nest destroyed.

Note that this nest is in the interandean valley where this species is very rare and hardly known from (Ridgely&Greenfield 2001) and also high in altitude for this species.

dataObject.dc:description:
Reproduction and general not well known. Only a few nests described from western Ecuador and Colombia. Nest described. Eggs described. Nestlings poorly described. Nesting behavior described a little.

For a summary, see Neotropical Birds Online.

For videos of this species at its nest see: Video1

dataObject.dc:title: Tersina viridis 27/08/2014
dataObject.dc:description:
Tersina viridis 27/08/2014

Nido de Tersina Viridis a 1.60 mts de altura en un barranco a borde de carretera rural, presenta dos polluelos aparentemente sanos, plumaje bien desarrollado y cubriendo casi que toda la piel. alimentados constantemente por sus padres (Hembra y macho) quienes vuelan sobre los copos de los árboles cazando insectos los cuales acumulan en el buche para posteriormente alimentar a sus polluelos.

Lat: 5.33.52 N
Long: 74.51.24 W

M.s.n.m. 510 mts

dataObject.dc:title: Summary
dataObject.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Reproduction
dataObject.dc:description:
Reproduction and general biology not well known. Only a few nests described from eastern Ecuador. Nest described. Eggs described. Nestlings poorly described. Nesting behavior during incubation described at one nest, otherwise poorly known.

For a summary, see Neotropical Birds Online.

This is a common species in many parts of its range, and on of the most easily observed of all Antpittas. For more exellent images of this species visit the Sapayoa Nature Photography page. For videos of this species at its nest see: Video1.

dataObject.dc:description:
Reproduction and general biology very poorly known. Only one nest described from western Ecuador. Nest described. Eggs undescribed. Nestlings poorly described. Nesting behavior poorly described.

For a summary, see Neotropical Birds Online.

For videos of this species at its nest see: Video1

dataObject.dc:title: Nest description
dataObject.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Reproduction
dataObject.dc:description: The single described nest was a large, thin-walled cup, and its contents were partially visible from below. It was attached by the rim, via two sparse ‘wings’ extending up on opposite sides to two narrow, parallel, horizontal branches (6 and 8 mm diameter). These attachment points extended c.3 cm above the rim and consisted of no more than 15–20 rootlets each. The nest was fairly uniformly comprised of thin, slightly branched rootlets, criss-crossed and interwoven,with only those circling the slightly thickened rim being coiled. The inner portion had a sparse, poorly defined lining of smooth, un-branched flexible fibres of unknown origin,as well as 4–5 black fungal rhizomorphs. The cup was 10 cm in diameter inside by 7.5cm deep. Externally the nest was 14 cm wide by 9 cm tall. (Greeney et al. 2012).

dataObject.dc:title: Egg description
dataObject.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Reproduction
dataObject.dc:description: A single egg, measured just prior to hatching, was 30.5 × 22.8 mm and weighed 7.9 g. The egg was slightly off-white with copious cinnamon and lavender flecks and narrow scrawls,concentrated at the larger end (Greeney et al. 2012).

dataObject.dc:title: Nestling description
dataObject.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Reproduction
dataObject.dc:description: A recently hatched nestling was completely devoid of natal down and had pinkish-colored skin which was slightly duskier dorsally. The bill was dark orange, yellower near the tip except for the dorsal portion of the mandible, which was dusky and bore a bright white egg tooth. The rictal flanges were bright yellow and the mouth lining was bright yelloworange.The nestling weighed 6.5 g and the right tarsus measured 11 mm (Greeney et al. 2012).

dataObject.dc:title: Summary
dataObject.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Reproduction
dataObject.dc:description:
Nest: described (n = 1) Egg: described (n = 1) Nestling: hatchling described (n = 1), older nestlings not described Nesting behavior: Very poorly known.

Frederickena fulva was originally described as a subspecies of Undulated Antshrike Frederickena unduligera but was recently elevated to species rank, based largely on vocalizations. Thus, in all but the most modern treatments, the taxon treated here was referred to as Undulated Antshrike. Fulvous Antshrike, as currently defined, is monotypic and occurs in the lowlands of westernmost Amazonia from southern Colombia to northern Peru.

dataObject.dc:title: Nest description
dataObject.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Reproduction
dataObject.dc:description: The nests of Tolmomyias sulphurescens are hanging pouches entered through a long, spout-like, downward-opening entrance tube which often opens well below the nesting chamber. They appear to be most often composed primarily of dark materials such as flexible fibers, rootlets, and fungal rhizomorphs.

dataObject.dc:title: Summary
dataObject.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Reproduction
dataObject.dc:description: Likely due to its large geographical distribution, the basic breeding biology of Tolmomyias sulphurescens is fairly well studied when compared to many species. Multiple descriptions of nests, eggs, and nesting habitat are available.

dataObject.dc:title: Slate-throated Gnatcatcher nest building
dataObject.dc:description:
Slate-throated Gnatcatcher nest building

Female about an hour after starting building a nest. The nest is in a fork on the outer part of the branch. Both parents were actively building the nest during the three hours we were in the canopy tower. It is about 12 m above ground. The picked small pieces of moss and lichens that were carefully selected and picked from dead branches. They also collected spiderweb. While building they tried out the nest by sitting down and move to make it comfortable. When we left after about three hours, they had made about half a cup. 7-10 am, 28-june 2013
